      <div purpose="landing-page-section">
        <div purpose="section-heading">
          <h2>What is the Model Context Protocol (MCP)?</h2>
          <p>The <a href="https://modelcontextprotocol.io/" target="_blank">Model Context Protocol (MCP)</a> is an open standard for connecting AI agents to external tools and data. An MCP server publishes a catalog of typed tools. Any compatible AI client, including Claude Desktop, Claude Code, and Cursor, can call those tools directly, without custom integration code.</p>
        </div>
        <div purpose="section-heading">
          <h2>What is the Fleet MCP server?</h2>
          <p>The Fleet MCP server puts Fleet and osquery on that standard. It turns Fleet's REST API into a catalog of purpose-built tools your AI agent can call natively: list hosts, run live osquery, check policy compliance, and investigate CVEs, all in plain English.</p>
        </div>
        <div purpose="section-image">
          <img alt="A diagram showing the gap between a security question and an actionable decision, bridged by the right query against the right hosts." src="/images/articles/natural-language-endpoint-security-fleet-mcp-gap-800x200@2x.png">
        </div>
        <div purpose="section-heading">
          <p>The slow part of endpoint security isn't accessing the data. It's getting from a question to the right query against the right hosts, in a form a human can act on. The Fleet data, the osquery, and your RBAC stay exactly where they are. The interface changes from plumbing to language, and the time from question to answer drops significantly.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div purpose="landing-page-section">
        <div purpose="section-heading">
          <h2>How the Fleet MCP server works</h2>
          <p>The Fleet MCP server has one job: turn Fleet's REST surface into a catalog of typed tools that obey the Model Context Protocol. Any MCP-compatible client can call them natively, with no glue code to maintain.</p>
        </div>
        <div purpose="architecture-image">
          <img alt="Architecture diagram. An AI client such as Claude Desktop, Cursor, or a Slack bot talks MCP to the Fleet MCP server, which talks REST to Fleet and osquery agents on every enrolled host." src="/images/articles/natural-language-endpoint-security-fleet-mcp-architecture-800x380@2x.png">
        </div>

      </div>

      <div purpose="landing-page-section">
        <div purpose="section-heading">
          <h2>Ask in plain English</h2>
          <p>These are real questions Fleet's own team asks the bot every week. The agent translates each one into the right query against the right hosts, then shows its work.</p>
        </div>
        <div purpose="example-prompts">
          <div purpose="prompt-card">
            <span purpose="prompt-tag">Supply chain</span>
            <p>"Are we affected by the recent axios npm exploit?"</p>
          </div>
          <div purpose="prompt-card">
            <span purpose="prompt-tag">Vulnerabilities</span>
            <p>"What are the top 10 CVEs to be aware of in my environment today?"</p>
          </div>
          <div purpose="prompt-card">
            <span purpose="prompt-tag">Inventory</span>
            <p>"Give me a summary of the devices in the Workstations fleet."</p>
          </div>
          <div purpose="prompt-card">
            <span purpose="prompt-tag">Compliance</span>
            <p>"Is this workstation compliant with all of our policies?"</p>
          </div>
          <div purpose="prompt-card">
            <span purpose="prompt-tag">Posture</span>
            <p>"How many hosts have SSH enabled?"</p>
          </div>
          <div purpose="prompt-card">
            <span purpose="prompt-tag">Policy authoring</span>
            <p>"Create a policy that fails if a host's battery is in poor condition."</p>
          </div>
          <div purpose="prompt-card">
            <span purpose="prompt-tag">Threat hunting</span>
            <p>"Based on this intel, scan every Linux host and show me the artifacts."</p>
          </div>
          <div purpose="prompt-card">
            <span purpose="prompt-tag">Lifecycle</span>
            <p>"Which hosts are most in need of a refresh?"</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div purpose="landing-page-section">
        <div purpose="feature-with-image">
          <div purpose="feature-text">
            <h3>Pre-CVE threat hunting in minutes</h3>
            <p>A public exploit drops with no CVE assigned and no vendor advisory yet. A traditional scanner returns nothing because there's nothing to match. With Fleet MCP, you drop the intel into Slack and tag the bot.</p>
            <p>The agent translates the artifacts in the writeup, such as kernel modules, sockets, and sysctls, into an osquery scan. It runs <code>prepare_live_query</code> to validate targets, then <code>run_live_query</code> across every Linux host on every fleet, and returns a per-host report with named risks and concrete next steps. No CVE required.</p>
          </div>
          <div purpose="feature-image">
            <img alt="A sanitized Slack thread. An operator pastes a public Linux privilege escalation proof of concept with no CVE yet, and Fleet reports per-host kernel versions, loaded modules, uptime, and risk notes." src="/images/articles/natural-language-endpoint-security-fleet-mcp-slack-thread-800x470@2x.png">
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div purpose="landing-page-section">
        <div purpose="feature-with-image">
          <div purpose="feature-image">
            <img alt="A CVE blast radius example. The operator asks how many systems have the latest Chrome vulnerabilities and how many are on the Workstations fleet, and Fleet reports the affected count with offline hosts called out." src="/images/articles/natural-language-endpoint-security-fleet-mcp-cve-blast-radius-800x280@2x.png">
          </div>
          <div purpose="feature-text">
            <h3>CVE blast radius, scoped to a fleet</h3>
            <p>The classic version of this question is a ticket, a curl loop, a spreadsheet, and 90 minutes. With Fleet MCP, it's a few plain-English questions: how many hosts are exposed, and which fleet are they on, because the answer determines who you message.</p>
            <div purpose="checklist">
              <p>Scopes to a fleet, so you message the right team, not everyone.</p>
              <p>Chains multiple CVE lookups in parallel and merges the results.</p>
              <p>Surfaces the offline cohort honestly, so the bound on the answer is always shown.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div purpose="landing-page-section">
        <div purpose="feature-with-image">
          <div purpose="feature-text">
            <h3>It knows what not to do</h3>
            <p>The most underrated property of a tool catalog is what's not in it. The Fleet MCP server can't read your keychain secrets, because macOS encrypts them at rest and osquery can only see metadata.</p>
            <p>When asked for secrets it doesn't have, the agent says so and offers the metadata it can see instead. That honest boundary is the behavior you want. A tool that pretends to do more than its underlying API allows is worse than no tool at all.</p>
          </div>
          <div purpose="feature-image">
            <div purpose="inline-chat-demo">
              <div purpose="inline-chat-row">
                <div purpose="inline-chat-avatar">op</div>
                <div purpose="inline-chat-bubble">
                  <p>What's in the keychain on user-a's MacBook?</p>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div purpose="inline-chat-row">
                <div purpose="inline-chat-avatar" class="fleet-avatar">F</div>
                <div purpose="inline-chat-bubble" class="fleet-bubble">
                  <p>I can't access keychain values. Secrets are encrypted by macOS; even with admin osquery, passwords and private keys aren't readable.</p>
                  <p>I <strong>can</strong> show metadata (labels, types, paths, creation dates) if that's useful. Want me to run that scoped to user-a's host?</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div purpose="landing-page-section">
        <div purpose="section-heading">
          <h2>What the Fleet MCP server won't do</h2>
          <p>A clear set of boundaries is what makes the tool trustworthy at fleet scale. These are deliberate design decisions, not gaps.</p>
        </div>
        <div purpose="feature-row">
          <div purpose="feature-item">
            <h5>It's not a vulnerability scanner</h5>
            <p>It's a translation layer for questions about your hosts. The authoritative data still lives in osquery and Fleet. Catalog tools answer "what CVEs apply?" Artifact queries answer "what do these hosts actually look like right now?"</p>
          </div>
          <div purpose="feature-item">
            <h5>It's not an autonomous responder</h5>
            <p>The agent can propose a policy, a script, or a query, but a human stays in the loop for anything that changes state. There's no delete-host tool and no arbitrary shell.</p>
          </div>
          <div purpose="feature-item">
            <h5>It doesn't hide its SQL</h5>
            <p>Every answer ships with the underlying osquery shown. If you can't review the query, you can't trust the answer. The transparency is the contract.</p>
          </div>
          <div purpose="feature-item">
            <h5>Writes require approval</h5>
            <p>Running a live query and saving a query are flagged as sensitive, so MCP clients prompt for confirmation before either one fires against your devices.</p>
          </div>
          <div purpose="feature-item">
            <h5>It respects your RBAC</h5>
            <p>The server acts through Fleet's REST API with your token, so existing role-based access control, fleet scoping, and audit logging all still apply.</p>
          </div>
          <div purpose="feature-item">
            <h5>It's not a substitute for knowing your stack</h5>
            <p>The tools encode structure, not literacy. An operator still needs to recognize, for example, that kernel modules only exist on Linux.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div purpose="landing-page-section" id="get-started">
        <div purpose="section-heading">
          <h2>Get started with Fleet MCP</h2>
          <p>The Fleet MCP server is open source and lives in the Fleet repository. Point it at your Fleet instance with two environment variables and connect it to your AI client.</p>
        </div>
        <div purpose="two-column-list">
          <div purpose="column-list">
            <h3>Build and run</h3>
            <pre purpose="code-block"><code>git clone https://github.com/fleetdm/fleet
cd fleet/tools/fleet-mcp
go build -o fleet-mcp .

# stdio transport for Claude Desktop
./fleet-mcp -transport stdio

# or SSE for Claude Code and Cursor
./fleet-mcp</code></pre>
          </div>
          <div purpose="column-list">
            <h3>Connect Claude Desktop</h3>
            <pre purpose="code-block"><code>{
  "mcpServers": {
    "fleet": {
      "command": "/path/to/fleet-mcp",
      "args": ["-transport", "stdio"],
      "env": {
        "FLEET_BASE_URL": "https://your-fleet.example.com",
        "FLEET_API_KEY": "YOUR_FLEET_API_KEY",
        "MCP_AUTH_TOKEN": "YOUR_MCP_AUTH_TOKEN"
      }
    }
  }
}</code></pre>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div purpose="button-row">
          <a purpose="cta-button" class="btn btn-primary" href="https://github.com/fleetdm/fleet/tree/main/tools/fleet-mcp" target="_blank">Get it on GitHub</a>
          <animated-arrow-button href="/guides/fleet-mcp">Read the setup guide</animated-arrow-button>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div purpose="landing-page-section">
        <div purpose="section-heading">
          <h2>Fleet MCP frequently asked questions</h2>
        </div>
        <div purpose="faq" class="d-flex flex-column">
          <div purpose="accordion" class="d-flex flex-column justify-content-start">
            <div purpose="accordion-body">
              <div purpose="accordion-item">
                <p purpose="accordion-header" id="mcp-faq__header1" style="cursor: pointer;" class="accordion" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#mcp-faq__body1" aria-controls="mcp-faq__body1">
                  What is the Model Context Protocol (MCP)?
                  <span class="fa fa-angle-down"></span>
                </p>
                <p purpose="faq-answer" id="mcp-faq__body1" class="collapse" aria-labelledby="mcp-faq__header1">
                  The Model Context Protocol is an open standard for connecting AI agents to external tools and data. An MCP server publishes a set of typed tools, and an MCP-compatible client such as Claude or Cursor can call those tools directly. Fleet's MCP server makes your Fleet instance one of those tool sources, so an AI agent can query your endpoints natively.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div purpose="accordion-item">
                <p purpose="accordion-header" id="mcp-faq__header2" style="cursor: pointer;" class="accordion" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#mcp-faq__body2" aria-controls="mcp-faq__body2">
                  What is the Fleet MCP server?
                  <span class="fa fa-angle-down"></span>
                </p>
                <p purpose="faq-answer" id="mcp-faq__body2" class="collapse" aria-labelledby="mcp-faq__header2">
                  The Fleet MCP server is a Model Context Protocol server for Fleet. It exposes Fleet's REST API and osquery as a catalog of typed tools that any MCP-compatible AI agent can call, so you can manage and investigate your devices in plain English instead of hand-writing API calls and SQL. It runs anywhere with stdio or SSE, including Claude Desktop, Claude Code, Cursor, and custom Slack bots.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div purpose="accordion-item">
                <p purpose="accordion-header" id="mcp-faq__header3" style="cursor: pointer;" class="accordion" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#mcp-faq__body3" aria-controls="mcp-faq__body3">
                  Which AI tools work with Fleet MCP?
                  <span class="fa fa-angle-down"></span>
                </p>
                <p purpose="faq-answer" id="mcp-faq__body3" class="collapse" aria-labelledby="mcp-faq__header3">
                  Any MCP-compatible client. Fleet uses it with Claude Desktop, Claude Code, and Cursor, and the same tool surface powers a custom Slack bot. The server supports both stdio and SSE transports, so it fits whichever client you prefer.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div purpose="accordion-item">
                <p purpose="accordion-header" id="mcp-faq__header4" style="cursor: pointer;" class="accordion" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#mcp-faq__body4" aria-controls="mcp-faq__body4">
                  What can I do with Fleet MCP?
                  <span class="fa fa-angle-down"></span>
                </p>
                <p purpose="faq-answer" id="mcp-faq__body4" class="collapse" aria-labelledby="mcp-faq__header4">
                  You can list and inspect hosts, run live osquery across your fleet, check per-host and per-policy compliance, investigate which devices are impacted by a CVE, and create saved queries. Teams use it for pre-CVE threat hunting, CVE blast-radius analysis scoped to a fleet, posture checks, and ad hoc inventory questions, all asked in plain English.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div purpose="accordion-item">
                <p purpose="accordion-header" id="mcp-faq__header4b" style="cursor: pointer;" class="accordion collapsed" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#mcp-faq__body4b" aria-controls="mcp-faq__body4b">
                  What will the Fleet MCP server not do?
                  <span class="fa fa-angle-down"></span>
                </p>
                <p purpose="faq-answer" id="mcp-faq__body4b" class="collapse" aria-labelledby="mcp-faq__header4b">
                  It's not a vulnerability scanner. It translates questions about your hosts into live osquery, but it doesn't replace a CVE catalog. It's not an autonomous incident responder. The agent can propose a policy, a script, or a query, but a human stays in the loop for anything that changes state. There's no delete-host tool and no arbitrary shell execution. It doesn't hide its SQL. Every answer includes the underlying osquery so you can review what ran. It doesn't pretend to access data that Fleet can't see. If you ask for keychain secrets, for example, it'll tell you those values are encrypted and offer the metadata it can read instead.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div purpose="accordion-item">
                <p purpose="accordion-header" id="mcp-faq__header5" style="cursor: pointer;" class="accordion" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#mcp-faq__body5" aria-controls="mcp-faq__body5">
                  Is Fleet MCP safe to run against production devices?
                  <span class="fa fa-angle-down"></span>
                </p>
                <p purpose="faq-answer" id="mcp-faq__body5" class="collapse" aria-labelledby="mcp-faq__header5">
                  Yes, with the expected controls. Live queries run as read-only osquery. The two tools that change state, running a live query and creating a saved query, are flagged as sensitive so MCP clients prompt for confirmation before they fire. There's no delete-host tool and no arbitrary shell. The server acts through Fleet's REST API with your token, so your existing RBAC, fleet scoping, and audit logging all still apply.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div purpose="accordion-item">
                <p purpose="accordion-header" id="mcp-faq__header6" style="cursor: pointer;" class="accordion" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#mcp-faq__body6" aria-controls="mcp-faq__body6">
                  How is Fleet MCP different from a vulnerability scanner?
                  <span class="fa fa-angle-down"></span>
                </p>
                <p purpose="faq-answer" id="mcp-faq__body6" class="collapse" aria-labelledby="mcp-faq__header6">
                  A scanner is bounded by its catalog. It can only tell you about CVEs it already knows. Fleet MCP runs the artifact query you describe against live osquery data, so it answers "what do these hosts actually look like right now?" That's what lets it respond to a public exploit before any CVE is assigned. When a CVE does exist, it can also pull the impact directly from Fleet.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div purpose="accordion-item">
                <p purpose="accordion-header" id="mcp-faq__header7" style="cursor: pointer;" class="accordion" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#mcp-faq__body7" aria-controls="mcp-faq__body7">
                  Is Fleet MCP open source?
                  <span class="fa fa-angle-down"></span>
                </p>
                <p purpose="faq-answer" id="mcp-faq__body7" class="collapse" aria-labelledby="mcp-faq__header7">
                  Yes. The Fleet MCP server is open source and lives in the Fleet repository at <a href="https://github.com/fleetdm/fleet/tree/main/tools/fleet-mcp" target="_blank">github.com/fleetdm/fleet</a>, under the same project as the rest of Fleet. You can read the code, run it on your own infrastructure, and extend it with new tools.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="d-flex flex-row justify-content-start">
              <p purpose="contact-note">Want to go deeper? Read the <a href="/securing/natural-language-endpoint-security-fleet-mcp">Fleet MCP manifesto</a> or <a href="/contact">talk to an engineer</a>.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
